WEBVTT

00:05.923 --> 00:08.884
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:08.884 --> 00:14.765
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:14.765 --> 00:16.808
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>Christoph Deringer.</i>

00:16.808 --> 00:19.520
I'm 50 years old, I think.

00:19.520 --> 00:22.356
<i>I don't keep track of my age</i>
<i>'cause I don't need to.</i>

00:23.190 --> 00:24.942
What year are we?

00:24.942 --> 00:26.902
<i>- My name's Brandon Austin.</i>

00:26.902 --> 00:28.654
<i>I've been making blades</i>
<i>for about six years.</i>

00:28.654 --> 00:30.739
I signed up
for "Forged in Fire"

00:30.739 --> 00:32.866
<i>because of the episode</i>
<i>with a contestant--</i>

00:32.866 --> 00:35.285
<i>Brandon--</i>
<i>cried multiple occasions.</i>

00:35.285 --> 00:37.246
<i>I can't let that go.</i>

00:37.246 --> 00:38.789
I came here to win
for all the Brandons out there.

00:38.789 --> 00:40.749
<i>My name's Wade Seiders.</i>

00:40.749 --> 00:42.960
<i>I've been making blades</i>
<i>for about 17 years.</i>

00:42.960 --> 00:44.836
I love problem solving.

00:44.836 --> 00:48.006
<i>Being able to forge</i>
<i>or complete a task--</i>

00:48.006 --> 00:49.508
that is fascinating to me.

00:49.508 --> 00:51.760
<i>My name is Matthew Christiano.</i>

00:51.760 --> 00:54.388
<i>I've been bladesmithing</i>
<i>for six years.</i>

00:54.388 --> 00:56.848
I'm walking past
this dump truck

00:56.848 --> 00:58.267
<i>through wet sand.</i>

00:58.267 --> 01:00.727
<i>That's right up my alley,</i>

01:00.727 --> 01:03.814
because I forge
in fields for fun.

01:03.814 --> 01:05.649
- Bladesmiths, welcome.

01:05.649 --> 01:07.776
I know you were probably
expecting The Forge,

01:07.776 --> 01:10.070
but today,
just to up the ante,

01:10.070 --> 01:12.364
we brought you
to our rock quarry.

01:12.364 --> 01:15.200
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:15.200 --> 01:16.743
You're here for three rounds

01:16.743 --> 01:18.787
of edged-weapon-making
competition,

01:18.787 --> 01:21.123
specifically designed to test
every aspect of your skills.

01:21.123 --> 01:22.874
And judging your progress

01:22.874 --> 01:24.793
is our panel
of esteemed judges.

01:24.793 --> 01:26.712
These are the guys
who are gonna determine

01:26.712 --> 01:29.047
which of you is the next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:29.047 --> 01:30.966
and also leaves here
with that check for ten grand.

01:30.966 --> 01:33.218
Two-time "Forged in Fire"
champion

01:33.218 --> 01:35.220
and fan favorite Ben Abbott,

01:35.220 --> 01:38.473
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker,

01:38.473 --> 01:42.352
Edged-weapons specialist
Doug Marcaida.

01:42.352 --> 01:44.479
You've noticed, on your anvils,
there's no steel.

01:44.479 --> 01:46.523
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:46.523 --> 01:48.191
That's because
you'll be choosing

01:48.191 --> 01:50.152
between round bar
and metal grate,

01:50.152 --> 01:52.195
sourced from this quarry.

01:52.195 --> 01:54.072
There's plenty of it out there.

01:54.072 --> 01:56.241
You'll have to choose
which is the better option.

01:56.241 --> 01:58.035
And as if that wasn't
hard enough,

01:58.035 --> 02:00.495
today you'll be using these...

02:00.495 --> 02:03.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:03.457 --> 02:05.584
Coal forges.

02:05.584 --> 02:09.296
<i>- Great.</i>
<i>Black snot, dust, and grit.</i>

02:09.296 --> 02:12.758
That's not something
that I enjoy very much.

02:12.758 --> 02:15.260
- Today you'll be using
these coal forges

02:15.260 --> 02:16.845
to make signature blades

02:16.845 --> 02:18.847
<i>that are between</i>
<i>12 and 14 inches.</i>

02:18.847 --> 02:20.515
<i>The overall length</i>
<i>of your weapon</i>

02:20.515 --> 02:22.726
must not exceed 22 inches.

02:22.726 --> 02:24.645
Keep in mind that,
in the second round,

02:24.645 --> 02:26.438
we'll return to The Forge,

02:26.438 --> 02:28.106
where you'll place a handle
onto your blades,

02:28.106 --> 02:30.025
turning them
into fully functional weapons

02:30.025 --> 02:32.235
that will then be tested
for strength and durability

02:32.235 --> 02:34.321
in a tile chop...

02:34.321 --> 02:38.492
and for edge retention
in a conveyor belt slice.

02:38.492 --> 02:40.786
Gentlemen, you will have
four hours in this round.

02:40.786 --> 02:43.330
There will be
no design period.

02:43.330 --> 02:46.917
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your four hours starts now.

02:46.917 --> 02:49.086
<i>[rock music]</i>

02:49.086 --> 02:51.088
So, Ben, which steel
would you pick?

02:51.088 --> 02:52.381
- If I was competing,
I'd be tempted

02:52.381 --> 02:53.757
by those steel grates

02:53.757 --> 02:55.676
because they're
easy to collect.

02:55.676 --> 02:57.427
But that round bar
would just be quicker to forge,

02:57.427 --> 02:58.637
provided you can get it
off the wall.

02:58.637 --> 03:00.806
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:00.806 --> 03:02.516
<i>- I'm grabbing</i>
<i>the large piece of steel</i>

03:02.516 --> 03:04.226
<i>because</i>
<i>the other piece of steel</i>

03:04.226 --> 03:05.769
<i>looked too skinny and small.</i>

03:05.769 --> 03:07.813
I didn't want
to have to forge-weld.

03:07.813 --> 03:09.272
- Thank you.

03:09.272 --> 03:11.191
- See, that's the beauty
of this.

03:11.191 --> 03:12.859
Even though you're
in competition with each other,

03:12.859 --> 03:15.112
the sportsmanship,
the camaraderie they have

03:15.112 --> 03:17.072
as bladesmiths--
it's beautiful to see

03:17.072 --> 03:19.324
that Brandon is getting
some of that round bar

03:19.324 --> 03:21.118
for Christoph and Wade.

03:21.118 --> 03:22.869
- Torch is over there...

03:22.869 --> 03:24.621
<i>I'm gonna make</i>
<i>a drop point hunter</i>

03:24.621 --> 03:26.206
<i>because I believe</i>
<i>it's a good design</i>

03:26.206 --> 03:27.249
<i>for chopping,</i>
<i>has a lot of meat</i>

03:27.249 --> 03:29.000
<i>behind the edge.</i>

03:29.000 --> 03:30.335
<i>What inspires me</i>
<i>when I'm making blades</i>

03:30.335 --> 03:32.212
is my imagination.

03:32.212 --> 03:35.215
I enjoy reading and
sci-fi-type movies and that.

03:35.215 --> 03:37.092
And you can make
those instruments and use them.

03:37.092 --> 03:39.761
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:39.761 --> 03:41.388
- Yeah, looks like
they're all going

03:41.388 --> 03:44.307
with a bar from the wall--
smart move.

03:44.307 --> 03:46.143
I think it might be 1084,
which is good steel.

03:46.143 --> 03:48.603
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:48.603 --> 03:51.565
- The nice thing about 1084
is it's a good, clean,

03:51.565 --> 03:53.692
easy-working steel.

03:53.692 --> 03:55.819
It's very forgiving.

03:55.819 --> 03:58.822
You'll be able to move that out
into a 2-by-1/4-inch bar

03:58.822 --> 04:00.699
without stressing yourself
too much.

04:00.699 --> 04:02.284
- The one thing you don't
want to see is sparks

04:02.284 --> 04:04.077
coming up with the fire.

04:04.077 --> 04:06.037
It means that the steel inside
is actually burning.

04:06.037 --> 04:08.331
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:08.331 --> 04:10.250
- Brandon is really having
a hard time

04:10.250 --> 04:12.335
getting his fire started.

04:12.335 --> 04:14.296
- Oh, my God.

04:14.296 --> 04:16.631
- You'll get it.
- [laughing]

04:16.631 --> 04:19.092
- I'm gonna make
the saber-style bowie.

04:19.092 --> 04:21.011
<i>I'm gonna have a lot of depth.</i>

04:21.011 --> 04:23.138
If I can run the fuller
with that, too,

04:23.138 --> 04:24.890
it'll give me the strength.

04:24.890 --> 04:26.850
<i>This is going great.</i>

04:26.850 --> 04:29.227
<i>Fire's going good,</i>
<i>exactly the way I want it.</i>

04:29.227 --> 04:30.479
Feeling good!

04:30.479 --> 04:32.647
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:32.647 --> 04:35.692
- I have a good idea of how
my knife is going to look.

04:35.692 --> 04:37.360
<i>I'm just gonna go</i>
<i>for something</i>

04:37.360 --> 04:38.320
<i>that I like to call</i>
<i>a chopper.</i>

04:38.320 --> 04:40.572
<i>It'll be wide.</i>

04:40.572 --> 04:43.074
<i>That width, I think,</i>
<i>will provide it</i>

04:43.074 --> 04:45.202
<i>with enough strength</i>
<i>to withstand</i>

04:45.202 --> 04:47.078
<i>the tile-breaking test.</i>

04:47.078 --> 04:49.706
This'll be a big-ass knife.

04:49.706 --> 04:52.125
- Christoph brought
Odin's hammer.

04:52.125 --> 04:53.752
- It'll be interesting to see

04:53.752 --> 04:55.504
how he moves steel
with that big old hammer.

04:55.504 --> 04:57.714
<i>- I'm gonna use</i>
<i>the big round bar.</i>

04:57.714 --> 05:00.300
The grate material looks
a little bit thin

05:00.300 --> 05:02.886
to make a 12-inch blade.

05:02.886 --> 05:05.680
<i>I have no clue</i>
<i>what I'm gonna design yet.</i>

05:05.680 --> 05:08.809
I think I'll see
what the steel tells me.

05:08.809 --> 05:09.935
[forge squeaking]

05:09.935 --> 05:12.020
- Son of a [bleep].

05:12.020 --> 05:14.481
- Already 20 minutes
into this competition,

05:14.481 --> 05:17.025
and one of our bladesmiths
doesn't have a fire,

05:17.025 --> 05:20.195
and that is a huge problem.

05:20.195 --> 05:21.905
<i>- I look around--</i>
<i>every other competitor</i>

05:21.905 --> 05:23.615
<i>has started the hammer work.</i>

05:23.615 --> 05:25.992
If I can't get
this fire going,

05:25.992 --> 05:28.703
I believe even my youngest boy
is gonna give me hell about it.

05:28.703 --> 05:30.622
I can't believe this.

05:30.622 --> 05:32.374
- It'd be nice to see him

05:32.374 --> 05:34.417
kind of pile a little bit more
coal up on there

05:34.417 --> 05:36.086
just make a
little vent hole for it

05:36.086 --> 05:38.213
so that hot flame
is moving out

05:38.213 --> 05:40.423
through one section,
heating that coal up.

05:40.423 --> 05:43.927
- My main goal today is
not to cry.

05:43.927 --> 05:45.804
[bleep] kidding me, man.

05:45.804 --> 05:48.473
[sighs shakily]

05:48.473 --> 05:51.810
- Bust that paper up
a little bit if you can.

05:51.810 --> 05:53.895
It's wound up tight.

05:53.895 --> 05:55.897
- Look at this--
Wade is actually

05:55.897 --> 05:58.358
taking time off to help Brandon
get his fire started.

05:58.358 --> 06:00.569
Teamwork works!
Look at that.

06:00.569 --> 06:02.571
- Did it, finally.

06:02.571 --> 06:04.739
- That's a fire.

06:04.739 --> 06:07.576
I'm very in tune to coal
and what it's capable of doing.

06:07.576 --> 06:09.536
<i>It's right up my alley,</i>
<i>and I just hope</i>

06:09.536 --> 06:11.913
<i>my body holds together</i>
<i>to finish.</i>

06:11.913 --> 06:13.957
- The last few times
he's pulled that steel out,

06:13.957 --> 06:15.542
it's got a good temperature.

06:15.542 --> 06:17.002
- What could
these smiths do, Dave,

06:17.002 --> 06:18.879
to know for a fact

06:18.879 --> 06:20.630
you're working the steel
at the right temperature?

06:20.630 --> 06:22.132
- It's really
just pulling it out.

06:22.132 --> 06:23.508
Don't leave it
in there forever.

06:23.508 --> 06:25.218
- You can burn the tip
right off

06:25.218 --> 06:26.303
of what you're working on
pretty quickly.

06:26.303 --> 06:27.929
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:27.929 --> 06:29.514
I love to see people
swing a hammer

06:29.514 --> 06:31.433
from above their head.

06:31.433 --> 06:32.934
That's how you know
they're gonna move metal.

06:32.934 --> 06:34.853
<i>- Currently</i>
<i>I am the lead blacksmith</i>

06:34.853 --> 06:36.813
<i>at Mountain Forge.</i>

06:36.813 --> 06:39.649
<i>Out of college,</i>
<i>I was a ski bum for a year,</i>

06:39.649 --> 06:41.526
<i>then I got the job</i>
<i>at the forge,</i>

06:41.526 --> 06:44.362
fabricating, and stayed there
for ten years.

06:44.362 --> 06:47.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:47.991 --> 06:50.577
- Brought his own Big Blu.
- Yep.

06:50.577 --> 06:52.996
- We've seen guys come in here
with monstrous hammers

06:52.996 --> 06:54.998
and get fatigued

06:54.998 --> 06:56.541
after the first round
of hammer blows.

06:56.541 --> 06:58.668
We have a disproportionately
large hammer

06:58.668 --> 07:01.254
compared to
the size of the human being.

07:01.254 --> 07:04.132
<i>- My big hammer is great.</i>

07:04.132 --> 07:06.092
<i>My biggest strengths</i>
<i>as a bladesmith</i>

07:06.092 --> 07:08.261
<i>are my hand-forging abilities.</i>

07:08.261 --> 07:12.474
I'm always doing something
with my hands.

07:12.474 --> 07:15.518
<i>I do a little bit</i>
<i>of origami now and then.</i>

07:15.518 --> 07:17.520
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:17.520 --> 07:19.731
<i>I like folding paper.</i>

07:19.731 --> 07:22.317
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:22.317 --> 07:26.196
- Bladesmiths!
90 minutes has elapsed!

07:26.196 --> 07:28.114
Brandon, coming along great.

07:28.114 --> 07:29.991
Started a little bit behind
everybody else.

07:29.991 --> 07:31.534
Finally starting to get

07:31.534 --> 07:33.870
down to that tang
and hammer on that.

07:33.870 --> 07:35.789
<i>- My fire's doing</i>
<i>really well now,</i>

07:35.789 --> 07:37.624
<i>so I figure I'll go ahead</i>
<i>and power through</i>

07:37.624 --> 07:39.376
and catch up,
'cause I lost a lot of time.

07:39.376 --> 07:41.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:41.586 --> 07:43.713
- [groans]

07:43.713 --> 07:45.131
- I just burnt my blade
in half.

07:45.131 --> 07:46.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:46.466 --> 07:48.593
<i>I'm gonna [bleep] lose it.</i>

07:48.593 --> 07:50.428
Can't believe I just [bleep]
burned up my steel.

07:50.428 --> 07:52.681
- He burnt off
about four inches of that bar.

07:52.681 --> 07:54.015
- Yep, and you can see
what happens

07:54.015 --> 07:55.350
once you get
to that temperature.

07:55.350 --> 07:57.310
The grain becomes
extremely brittle.

07:57.310 --> 07:59.229
- [bleep] kidding me.

07:59.229 --> 08:00.772
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:00.772 --> 08:03.566
- Oh!
- Oh!

08:03.566 --> 08:06.152
- Half of Wade's blade
just burnt off.

08:06.152 --> 08:08.279
- He just heated
that steel so much,

08:08.279 --> 08:11.366
hit it once with a hammer, four
inches fell from that steel.

08:11.366 --> 08:13.326
- And that's exactly what
happened on Brandon's blade.

08:13.326 --> 08:14.619
- [bleep].

08:14.619 --> 08:16.246
I got my blade too hot.

08:16.246 --> 08:18.164
I'm just mad at myself...

08:18.164 --> 08:19.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:19.582 --> 08:21.209
<i>For that novice mistake.</i>

08:21.209 --> 08:23.586
I feel like I'm done.

08:23.586 --> 08:25.422
- I think that we have a smith

08:25.422 --> 08:26.629
who's out
of this competition already.

08:28.989 --> 08:31.068
<i>- I can't believe I just</i>
<i>[bleep] burned up my steel.</i>

08:31.068 --> 08:33.821
I just want to kick the fire
over and just [bleep] leave.

08:33.821 --> 08:36.240
- Out here,
with the lighting like it is,

08:36.240 --> 08:38.993
is it more difficult
to judge the temperature

08:38.993 --> 08:40.661
of your steel?
- Absolutely.

08:40.661 --> 08:42.705
'Cause the sun comes out
and it goes away,

08:42.705 --> 08:45.374
everything is dependent
on the lighting.

08:45.374 --> 08:47.001
- I'm an extremely
competitive person.

08:47.001 --> 08:48.919
I do not like to lose.

08:48.919 --> 08:50.588
<i>I'm getting new steel</i>
<i>and starting over.</i>

08:50.588 --> 08:52.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:52.923 --> 08:55.342
<i>- I feel like I'm done.</i>

08:55.342 --> 08:57.219
And I'm just mad at myself,

08:57.219 --> 08:59.722
<i>but quitting is not an option.</i>

08:59.722 --> 09:01.974
<i>It's not even in my DNA.</i>

09:01.974 --> 09:03.601
- Way to go, Wade.

09:03.601 --> 09:05.811
"I lost my tang.
I'll make a hidden tang."

09:05.811 --> 09:08.230
Just change the plan--
that's the way to go.

09:08.230 --> 09:10.399
<i>- I might have to change</i>
<i>my blade style.</i>

09:10.399 --> 09:12.151
I'll go for a seax.

09:12.151 --> 09:14.153
<i>I have quite</i>
<i>a bit of steel left,</i>

09:14.153 --> 09:16.280
<i>but this thing</i>
<i>is gonna be thinned out</i>

09:16.280 --> 09:18.782
<i>a little more than I like.</i>

09:18.782 --> 09:20.826
<i>- I'm starting my new blade,</i>
<i>and the first thing</i>

09:20.826 --> 09:23.203
<i>that's running through my mind</i>
<i>is not overheating it.</i>

09:23.203 --> 09:25.372
I'm not gonna cry.
I don't care what happened.

09:25.372 --> 09:27.374
I don't care how many times
I messed up.

09:27.374 --> 09:29.043
<i>I'm not gonna burn</i>
<i>my blade again,</i>

09:29.043 --> 09:30.669
<i>because I have to turn</i>
<i>something in.</i>

09:30.669 --> 09:32.004
<i>I can't just quit.</i>

09:32.004 --> 09:33.797
- One of my concerns here

09:33.797 --> 09:35.966
is he's been hammering that
when it's cold.

09:35.966 --> 09:37.760
If he keeps hammering
on cold steel like that,

09:37.760 --> 09:40.554
he could develop cracks.

09:40.554 --> 09:42.473
- I got my handle
shaped out,

09:42.473 --> 09:45.100
so I'm gonna cut off
the remainder of the steel

09:45.100 --> 09:47.019
and start forging my point.

09:47.019 --> 09:48.854
- Smart work--
instead of cutting it off flat,

09:48.854 --> 09:50.189
he's cutting an angle into it.

09:50.189 --> 09:52.066
Now we should see him start

09:52.066 --> 09:54.276
really to work those bevels
up towards that tip.

09:54.276 --> 09:57.279
<i>- Today I feel like</i>
<i>the coal's feeding me--</i>

09:57.279 --> 10:00.115
the other bladesmiths are
feeding me this great energy.

10:00.115 --> 10:02.743
<i>It's time to start</i>
<i>spreading out this blade.</i>

10:02.743 --> 10:04.578
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:04.578 --> 10:07.206
<i>Focus isn't one</i>
<i>of my strong points.</i>

10:07.206 --> 10:09.291
I'm hearing cuss words.

10:09.291 --> 10:12.169
- [bleep], [bleep] hot.

10:12.169 --> 10:14.505
<i>- I keep noticing Christoph</i>
<i>disappearing.</i>

10:14.505 --> 10:16.173
<i>I'm starting to be</i>
<i>a little concerned for him--</i>

10:16.173 --> 10:18.550
that he won't get his blade
finished in time.

10:18.550 --> 10:21.637
- Christoph hasn't been back
over to the forge in a while.

10:21.637 --> 10:23.889
He's been battling
with his steel.

10:23.889 --> 10:26.809
It's really not
looking good for him.

10:26.809 --> 10:28.352
<i>- The eight-pound hammer</i>
<i>is great</i>

10:28.352 --> 10:30.145
<i>for starting things,</i>

10:30.145 --> 10:32.648
but I'm not built
to swing it all day long.

10:32.648 --> 10:35.526
<i>I'm starting to get hot spots</i>
<i>on my hands.</i>

10:35.526 --> 10:37.361
I can feel blisters forming.

10:37.361 --> 10:39.697
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:39.697 --> 10:42.991
<i>My competitors are monsters.</i>
<i>Jeez, these are big guys.</i>

10:42.991 --> 10:46.370
<i>I'm half the size</i>
<i>of everybody else around here.</i>

10:46.370 --> 10:48.580
I'm just gonna have a break.

10:48.580 --> 10:50.749
There's still time left.

10:50.749 --> 10:53.001
<i>I'm not worried at all.</i>

10:53.001 --> 10:57.339
- Bladesmiths!
You only have 60 minutes!

10:57.339 --> 10:59.425
- I'm worried about that clock.

10:59.425 --> 11:01.844
<i>There's an hour left,</i>
<i>and I'm trying to catch up.</i>

11:01.844 --> 11:03.929
<i>Matt's got a blade forged out,</i>

11:03.929 --> 11:05.723
<i>and Wade's blade's</i>
<i>looking pretty nice as well.</i>

11:05.723 --> 11:07.182
I believe I can get it done,

11:07.182 --> 11:08.642
but it definitely
won't be the blade

11:08.642 --> 11:10.853
that I had planned to do.

11:10.853 --> 11:13.439
- What I'm doing now is...

11:13.439 --> 11:15.941
trying to clean my blade up
after stretching it out

11:15.941 --> 11:18.068
before I quench.

11:18.068 --> 11:20.112
This quench has to be right.

11:20.112 --> 11:23.365
This is where luck comes
into play.

11:23.365 --> 11:25.159
<i>If this doesn't work,</i>
<i>I'm going home.</i>

11:25.159 --> 11:27.161
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:27.161 --> 11:29.121
- All right,
Wade's in the quench.

11:29.121 --> 11:30.789
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:30.789 --> 11:33.041
- Fabulous.

11:33.041 --> 11:34.918
I'm ecstatic.
It's finished.

11:34.918 --> 11:37.296
<i>This wasn't the blade</i>
<i>I set out to make,</i>

11:37.296 --> 11:40.758
<i>but this was a decent</i>
<i>second option to me.</i>

11:40.758 --> 11:44.094
Person in front of me
is Matthew, young strong buck.

11:44.094 --> 11:46.013
Even though he's Californian,
he can forge.

11:46.013 --> 11:48.390
Looks like he should be
on a surfboard.

11:48.390 --> 11:50.851
- There he goes.
Boom.

11:50.851 --> 11:53.061
Matthew has really been
cruising along

11:53.061 --> 11:56.273
very steadily,
no problems there.

11:56.273 --> 11:58.317
- I'm feeling pretty good
right now.

11:58.317 --> 12:00.861
<i>I'm gonna start grinding down</i>
<i>on it to make it smooth</i>

12:00.861 --> 12:03.030
<i>and to give it a better</i>
<i>feeling in the hand.</i>

12:03.030 --> 12:06.867
Sleek lines and clean designs.
That's my style.

12:06.867 --> 12:10.537
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:10.537 --> 12:12.748
[sighing]
[bleep].

12:12.748 --> 12:15.292
I see two little stress
fractures

12:15.292 --> 12:16.919
in the spine of the knife.

12:16.919 --> 12:19.505
<i>I am heartbroken.</i>

12:19.505 --> 12:21.256
I am very nervous
that there's gonna be

12:21.256 --> 12:23.967
more of these cracks
throughout the blade.

12:23.967 --> 12:26.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:26.220 --> 12:28.263
- Christoph
came out of the gate

12:28.263 --> 12:30.432
with the big hammer
for a few strokes.

12:30.432 --> 12:32.768
Now he's kind of defaulting
to that pace

12:32.768 --> 12:34.812
where his hammer blows
are steady,

12:34.812 --> 12:36.605
everything's rhythmic.

12:36.605 --> 12:40.776
- That break he took
has really reset him.

12:40.776 --> 12:43.987
- The blade looks kind of
like a Mediterranean dirk.

12:43.987 --> 12:46.198
<i>My main concern is length.</i>

12:46.198 --> 12:48.325
I'm just gonna stretch
the front section,

12:48.325 --> 12:51.161
the front third of the blade,
until I get enough length.

12:51.161 --> 12:53.038
- It's starting
to look like something.

12:53.038 --> 12:54.748
- Hope it's a 12-inch
something.

12:54.748 --> 12:55.958
- Ten!

12:55.958 --> 12:57.209
Nine!

12:57.209 --> 12:58.335
Eight!

12:58.335 --> 13:00.128
Seven! Six!

13:00.128 --> 13:01.338
Five!

13:01.338 --> 13:03.340
Four! Three!

13:03.340 --> 13:05.092
Two! One!

13:05.092 --> 13:07.094
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.

13:07.094 --> 13:09.346
This forging round is over.

13:09.346 --> 13:11.682
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:11.682 --> 13:14.309
<i>- My blade's a chopper.</i>
<i>It's gonna chop.</i>

13:14.309 --> 13:15.978
Is it gonna break?
Maybe.

13:15.978 --> 13:17.771
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:17.771 --> 13:19.898
- Bladesmiths, welcome
to The Forge.

13:19.898 --> 13:21.525
You coal-forged
signature blades

13:21.525 --> 13:23.193
in your signature style.

13:23.193 --> 13:24.778
Now it's time for the judges

13:24.778 --> 13:26.822
to take a closer look.
at your work.

13:26.822 --> 13:29.449
Matthew, please present
your blade to the judges.

13:29.449 --> 13:31.451
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:31.451 --> 13:32.911
<i>- I'm very impressed</i>
<i>with your hammer work.</i>

13:32.911 --> 13:35.247
This looks fantastic...

13:35.247 --> 13:38.917
except these two major cracks.

13:38.917 --> 13:40.627
- You mastered the heat.

13:40.627 --> 13:42.337
He who controls the heat

13:42.337 --> 13:44.631
moves more metal
with every beat.

13:44.631 --> 13:46.883
But overall,
impressive, sir.

13:46.883 --> 13:48.677
- Thank you.
- All right, Wade.

13:48.677 --> 13:50.470
Let's see what your work
has to say.

13:50.470 --> 13:52.514
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:52.514 --> 13:54.516
- Well, Wade,
I love the shape.

13:54.516 --> 13:56.268
I love the little bit
of a clip point.

13:56.268 --> 13:57.853
There is a tiny bit of a warp,

13:57.853 --> 13:59.354
but I think it's within
grinder range.

13:59.354 --> 14:01.189
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:01.189 --> 14:02.608
- As soon as you had a problem
with the tang

14:02.608 --> 14:03.942
by burning some
of that metal off,

14:03.942 --> 14:05.736
you didn't miss a beat at all.

14:05.736 --> 14:07.529
You adapted, you overcome,
you improvised,

14:07.529 --> 14:09.865
and then you turned out
this beautiful shape.

14:09.865 --> 14:11.950
Good job, sir.
- Thank you, sir.

14:11.950 --> 14:13.493
- Brandon, you're up.

14:13.493 --> 14:14.911
Please present your work
to the judges.

14:14.911 --> 14:17.080
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:17.080 --> 14:19.666
<i>- Brandon, a bit of</i>
<i>a rough shape, as it sits.</i>

14:19.666 --> 14:22.753
There's a lot of cracking.

14:22.753 --> 14:24.588
- I like the drop
that you have over here.

14:24.588 --> 14:26.715
It feels like
a good slashing weapon.

14:26.715 --> 14:28.717
Overall, thank you
for persevering

14:28.717 --> 14:30.886
through that heat
and that sun.

14:30.886 --> 14:33.388
Good job.
- Thank you.

14:33.388 --> 14:35.557
- Christoph, please present
your work to the judges.

14:35.557 --> 14:37.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:37.601 --> 14:39.144
<i>- Your use of the cross peen</i>
<i>on this blade</i>

14:39.144 --> 14:40.228
<i>was great to watch.</i>

14:40.228 --> 14:41.688
I love the fact you got

14:41.688 --> 14:43.690
this integral bolster on here.

14:43.690 --> 14:45.525
It's a really nice touch,

14:45.525 --> 14:47.527
and the way you came back
from kind of burning out

14:47.527 --> 14:49.279
for a second there
was really good to see.

14:49.279 --> 14:51.657
- I really like the shape
of this.

14:51.657 --> 14:53.659
We were nervous
about the length of it.

14:53.659 --> 14:55.911
I know that you were stretching
and stretching and stretching.

14:55.911 --> 14:57.496
We'll see if it made it.

14:57.496 --> 14:59.498
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:59.498 --> 15:01.625
- Bladesmiths, the judges will
now go into deliberation.

15:01.625 --> 15:03.251
While they do that,

15:03.251 --> 15:04.378
you're gonna leave your blades
on this table

15:04.378 --> 15:05.962
and step off The Forge floor.

15:05.962 --> 15:11.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:11.968 --> 15:13.970
- [exhales deeply]

15:13.970 --> 15:15.847
- Well, gentlemen, we've got
four completed blades.

15:15.847 --> 15:17.265
Let's go over the details.

15:17.265 --> 15:19.101
We'll start
with Matthew's blade here.

15:19.101 --> 15:20.727
- Matt, they got your blade.
- They got my blade?

15:20.727 --> 15:21.770
Oh, God.

15:21.770 --> 15:23.814
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:23.814 --> 15:25.565
<i>- He came up</i>
<i>with a great profile.</i>

15:25.565 --> 15:27.192
I like the fact
that he started

15:27.192 --> 15:29.403
with the tang
and worked forward.

15:29.403 --> 15:32.239
He shaped everything to here
and then just worked that down.

15:32.239 --> 15:34.282
I'm not crazy
about the way this is set up.

15:34.282 --> 15:35.784
It's just really wide.

15:35.784 --> 15:37.661
- The one issue
about his blade

15:37.661 --> 15:39.746
are those cracks right there.

15:39.746 --> 15:41.623
The good thing is that he was
able to make it wide,

15:41.623 --> 15:43.500
so that if he does make
any corrections in there,

15:43.500 --> 15:46.753
he'll still have enough blade
to perform in our test.

15:46.753 --> 15:49.506
- All right, let's move on
to Wade's blade.

15:49.506 --> 15:52.175
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:52.175 --> 15:54.553
- I really like
the broke-back-seax shape.

15:54.553 --> 15:57.431
You know, he lost a bit
of his steel early on.

15:57.431 --> 15:59.349
I think that that worked out
in his favor,

15:59.349 --> 16:00.892
because otherwise,
it might have been a big,

16:00.892 --> 16:02.853
stouter, heavier blade.

16:02.853 --> 16:04.896
I think he did a good job.

16:04.896 --> 16:06.940
<i>- All right, let's move on</i>
<i>to our next bladesmith.</i>

16:06.940 --> 16:08.024
<i>What do we think</i>
<i>of Brandon's work?</i>

16:08.024 --> 16:10.402
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:10.402 --> 16:12.279
<i>- He fought that fire</i>

16:12.279 --> 16:14.406
and rarely getting this
up to a working heat.

16:14.406 --> 16:17.367
He was just pounding cold steel
the whole time, and it shows.

16:17.367 --> 16:18.702
I mean,
there are cracks on this

16:18.702 --> 16:20.579
that go in every direction.

16:20.579 --> 16:22.414
<i>- Surface cracks are okay,</i>

16:22.414 --> 16:24.249
but it's at a critical area.

16:24.249 --> 16:25.959
You got cracks over here

16:25.959 --> 16:27.878
on the spine and on the edge,
and the edge

16:27.878 --> 16:30.088
is what makes contact
to what we're cutting.

16:30.088 --> 16:32.299
<i>- All right, moving on</i>
<i>to our last bladesmith,</i>

16:32.299 --> 16:33.467
<i>and that is Christoph.</i>

16:33.467 --> 16:36.052
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:36.052 --> 16:37.763
- It's good to see him
pull out the fullers

16:37.763 --> 16:40.307
to put this transition in here
to the integral guard.

16:40.307 --> 16:41.892
That's really impressive.

16:41.892 --> 16:45.312
- This is such a classic
knife shape.

16:45.312 --> 16:46.813
He really pulled his
full toolbox out

16:46.813 --> 16:48.857
and hammered in
a distal taper.

16:48.857 --> 16:50.442
Now, some of that
was just panic

16:50.442 --> 16:52.402
to get enough length
out of that tip,

16:52.402 --> 16:54.946
which is, of course, the...

16:54.946 --> 16:56.156
big question.

16:56.156 --> 17:01.995
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:01.995 --> 17:04.164
- Right on the line.
- Wow.

17:04.164 --> 17:05.791
- All right, judges,
all these things

17:05.791 --> 17:07.375
taken into consideration--
Doug, I need to know

17:07.375 --> 17:08.627
if you made
your final decision.

17:08.627 --> 17:09.836
- Yes, I have.
- Dave?

17:09.836 --> 17:11.379
- Oh, yeah.
- Ben?

17:11.379 --> 17:13.173
- Yes.
- Let's go tell our smiths.

17:13.173 --> 17:14.382
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:14.382 --> 17:15.967
- Bladesmiths,

17:15.967 --> 17:17.302
the judges' deliberation
is complete,

17:17.302 --> 17:19.304
and they've made
a final decision.

17:19.304 --> 17:21.848
It's time for one of you smiths
to leave The Forge.

17:21.848 --> 17:24.643
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:24.643 --> 17:27.729
Brandon, your blade
didn't make the cut.

17:27.729 --> 17:29.231
- Brandon,
you fought hard out there,

17:29.231 --> 17:31.108
fighting with
the ever-changing light,

17:31.108 --> 17:33.902
the coal forge kind of
acting up on you,

17:33.902 --> 17:35.570
but in the end,
what it came down to

17:35.570 --> 17:37.572
are those multiple cracks
in that blade,

17:37.572 --> 17:39.449
<i>and we just don't see a way</i>
<i>you could fix those</i>

17:39.449 --> 17:42.077
in the second round,
but thank you for your work.

17:42.077 --> 17:45.205
- Brandon,
please surrender your weapon.

17:45.205 --> 17:48.375
<i>- Yeah, I definitely came here</i>
<i>to prove that I wouldn't cry</i>

17:48.375 --> 17:49.668
and prove that
I can make a blade,

17:49.668 --> 17:51.878
<i>and I 75% achieved that goal.</i>

17:51.878 --> 17:53.755
<i>I didn't quite make a blade</i>
<i>that was functional.</i>

17:53.755 --> 17:55.632
But I didn't cry.

17:55.632 --> 17:57.509
<i>Someone's got to go</i>
<i>in the first round,</i>

17:57.509 --> 17:59.136
and I'm that guy.

17:59.136 --> 18:01.138
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:01.138 --> 18:03.223
- Congratulations, bladesmiths,
you've made it

18:03.223 --> 18:04.891
to the second round
of this competition.

18:04.891 --> 18:06.810
And now that your blades
have been tempered,

18:06.810 --> 18:08.103
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

18:08.103 --> 18:10.230
by attaching handles to them.

18:10.230 --> 18:12.899
You will have three hours
in which to complete your work.

18:12.899 --> 18:14.860
But keep in mind,
after this round,

18:14.860 --> 18:17.404
your blades will be tested
for strength and durability

18:17.404 --> 18:19.739
in a ceramic tile chop...

18:19.739 --> 18:22.993
and for edge retention
in a conveyor belt slice.

18:22.993 --> 18:24.369
Good luck, bladesmiths.

18:24.369 --> 18:26.788
Your three hours starts...now.

18:26.788 --> 18:28.498
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:28.498 --> 18:29.958
- Here we go.
- Off to the races.

18:29.958 --> 18:31.751
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:31.751 --> 18:33.587
- Christoph, heading over
to the grinder--

18:33.587 --> 18:35.797
does he have
the most work to do?

18:35.797 --> 18:37.340
- I don't think so--
Matthew's got

18:37.340 --> 18:39.092
a whole back of a blade
to grind away.

18:39.092 --> 18:40.927
- [laughing] Oh, yeah.

18:40.927 --> 18:42.429
- The first thing I'm gonna do
in round two

18:42.429 --> 18:43.930
<i>is eliminate those cracks.</i>

18:43.930 --> 18:45.974
I have to profile
the whole spine,

18:45.974 --> 18:47.767
<i>which is over 14 inches long.</i>

18:47.767 --> 18:49.227
I've got to take almost
a quarter inch

18:49.227 --> 18:51.146
off the back of this knife.

18:51.146 --> 18:53.440
- Matthew's design right now--
it's still thick,

18:53.440 --> 18:55.442
whereas Christoph is already
starting out

18:55.442 --> 18:58.069
with a very lean blade,
so the more he grinds,

18:58.069 --> 18:59.654
the lighter that blade's
gonna be,

18:59.654 --> 19:01.448
and we're gonna do
some chopping.

19:01.448 --> 19:04.326
<i>- My plan for round two</i>
<i>is to make a shiny,</i>

19:04.326 --> 19:06.828
<i>poke-y thing that cuts,</i>
<i>with a handle-y bit</i>

19:06.828 --> 19:09.497
<i>on the other side that doesn't</i>
<i>hurt your fingers too much.</i>

19:09.497 --> 19:11.958
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:11.958 --> 19:14.336
- Christoph wants
to modify the ruler.

19:14.336 --> 19:16.296
- Oh, he's actually even
cut a notch

19:16.296 --> 19:18.423
for the integral bolster
and put it all the way across.

19:18.423 --> 19:20.342
- Interesting idea.

19:20.342 --> 19:22.219
- Either that,
or he's given up

19:22.219 --> 19:23.762
on the blade he started with,
and he's gonna

19:23.762 --> 19:25.055
make a knife out of the ruler.
- [laughs]

19:25.055 --> 19:27.974
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:27.974 --> 19:30.227
- I'm putting a guard
on this blade

19:30.227 --> 19:32.812
<i>because of the historical</i>
<i>attributes it has</i>

19:32.812 --> 19:34.189
<i>for the seax.</i>

19:34.189 --> 19:35.732
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:35.732 --> 19:37.567
Dirty dog!

19:37.567 --> 19:40.320
<i>Normally, I use a drift</i>
<i>for the guard,</i>

19:40.320 --> 19:42.364
but I didn't do that this time.

19:42.364 --> 19:44.241
<i>I was using the Dremel</i>
<i>to get a tighter fit.</i>

19:44.241 --> 19:45.617
[tool whirring]

19:45.617 --> 19:47.202
[bleep].

19:47.202 --> 19:49.329
These tools--
I'm breaking them.

19:49.329 --> 19:51.873
Oh!
Why is that doing that?

19:51.873 --> 19:54.334
I'm not functioning properly.
I can't think.

19:54.334 --> 19:56.127
[metal clatters]

19:56.127 --> 19:57.921
Son of a [bleep].

19:57.921 --> 20:01.258
I'm spending way too much time
on this guard.

20:01.258 --> 20:03.385
- One hour has elapsed!

20:03.385 --> 20:05.220
- All of a sudden,
Matthew jumped out,

20:05.220 --> 20:06.846
bam, he's working
on handle now.

20:06.846 --> 20:08.765
When did that happen?

20:08.765 --> 20:09.891
<i>- I think I've gotten rid</i>
<i>of the cracks</i>

20:09.891 --> 20:12.060
<i>that were in my blade,</i>

20:12.060 --> 20:14.604
so I pick some sort
of synthetic material.

20:14.604 --> 20:17.399
<i>I picked red 'cause</i>
<i>it's a passionate color</i>

20:17.399 --> 20:19.192
and I'm a passionate person.

20:19.192 --> 20:21.695
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:21.695 --> 20:23.405
<i>When the drill bit goes</i>
<i>through the scales,</i>

20:23.405 --> 20:25.198
<i>it flexes a little,</i>

20:25.198 --> 20:28.493
and makes a little bit
of a bend in my hole.

20:28.493 --> 20:31.371
<i>My next pin</i>
<i>isn't going through.</i>

20:31.371 --> 20:33.373
[groans]

20:33.373 --> 20:35.250
<i>I abandon that pin</i>

20:35.250 --> 20:37.502
<i>and find a piece</i>
<i>of brass tubing</i>

20:37.502 --> 20:40.213
<i>to make a nice little</i>
<i>lanyard hole.</i>

20:40.213 --> 20:41.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:41.923 --> 20:43.591
- This guy... [laughs]
- He's hilarious.

20:43.591 --> 20:45.468
- I didn't ask him
what he was smelling for.

20:45.468 --> 20:47.846
Didn't want to offend the guy.

20:47.846 --> 20:50.557
<i>- The purpleheart that I chose</i>
<i>feels heavy enough</i>

20:50.557 --> 20:53.101
<i>to counterbalance</i>
<i>the weight of my knife...</i>

20:53.101 --> 20:55.520
hopefully.

20:55.520 --> 20:57.063
- Has he put any pins in there?

20:57.063 --> 20:59.065
- I don't think so.

20:59.065 --> 21:01.484
- When you have
an integral bolster,

21:01.484 --> 21:04.779
if you try to pin
both scales on at once,

21:04.779 --> 21:08.408
one of them will always
slide out of alignment,

21:08.408 --> 21:10.952
<i>and I'm trying to avoid</i>
<i>the sloppy look.</i>

21:10.952 --> 21:13.663
This isn't the '80s.

21:13.663 --> 21:16.833
- If he drills through that
wood and into that tang,

21:16.833 --> 21:20.170
doesn't it have the possibility
of popping his scale off?

21:20.170 --> 21:21.546
- Oh, yes.

21:21.546 --> 21:23.548
<i>- If things go well,</i>

21:23.548 --> 21:27.218
<i>drilling the holes</i>
<i>through everything at once</i>

21:27.218 --> 21:29.137
saves a lot of time.

21:29.137 --> 21:31.389
<i>If you're working</i>
<i>under a time limit,</i>

21:31.389 --> 21:32.807
<i>you take chances.</i>

21:32.807 --> 21:33.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:33.892 --> 21:35.935
- Unreal.

21:35.935 --> 21:39.314
This guard is taking me
way too long.

21:39.314 --> 21:42.150
<i>So I'm making a drift</i>
<i>out of this,</i>

21:42.150 --> 21:44.194
<i>then do it the way</i>
<i>I just normally do it.</i>

21:44.194 --> 21:47.072
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:47.072 --> 21:48.782
My plan for making the handle--

21:48.782 --> 21:51.618
<i>I'm gonna pick</i>
<i>some strong, hard wood.</i>

21:51.618 --> 21:54.579
I need some size, because
I'm doing a hidden tang.

21:54.579 --> 21:57.415
- Oh, God.
Not a burn-in.

21:57.415 --> 21:59.292
- Oh, man, these burn-throughs

21:59.292 --> 22:01.461
have been disastrous
in the past.

22:01.461 --> 22:03.380
<i>- I'm doing a burn-through</i>

22:03.380 --> 22:05.924
because it will go
into the wood handle faster

22:05.924 --> 22:08.134
and the burn
will expand it out,

22:08.134 --> 22:11.304
<i>and I'll have a tight fit.</i>

22:11.304 --> 22:14.224
- We've had burn-throughs
where, in the last second,

22:14.224 --> 22:16.643
they went to tap
that handle on and pop!

22:16.643 --> 22:18.520
<i>- This is extremely dangerous.</i>

22:18.520 --> 22:20.688
I'm putting a lot of pressure
on the handle.

22:20.688 --> 22:22.857
- Ooh. I don't want to
see him leaning on it

22:22.857 --> 22:24.150
like that.
- Yeah... [stammers]

22:24.150 --> 22:25.443
- When that thing cracks,

22:25.443 --> 22:26.653
he's got hot steel
in his hand.

22:26.653 --> 22:28.905
- If this breaks, I'm done.

22:28.905 --> 22:30.323
- Don't do that.

22:30.323 --> 22:31.686
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:44.032 --> 22:45.048
- [laughing] It's actually
pretty good, man.

22:45.048 --> 22:46.883
<i>- Lady Luck was on my side.</i>

22:46.883 --> 22:48.552
I'll go with it.

22:48.552 --> 22:50.178
- 15 minutes!

22:50.178 --> 22:52.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:52.014 --> 22:53.890
Look at Matthew's blade,
with that red handle.

22:53.890 --> 22:55.392
Man, that thing is sexy.

22:55.392 --> 22:57.644
Is there any worry
that those cracks

22:57.644 --> 23:00.105
might exist elsewhere
in his blade?

23:00.105 --> 23:01.815
- It is possible
there's others.

23:01.815 --> 23:03.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:03.609 --> 23:06.153
<i>- The cracks are still</i>
<i>in my head.</i>

23:06.153 --> 23:09.156
<i>They've positioned</i>
<i>my knife to fail.</i>

23:09.156 --> 23:11.617
My competition has about
as much experience

23:11.617 --> 23:14.536
as I am old,
so I hope my knife

23:14.536 --> 23:15.704
<i>can hold up to theirs.</i>

23:15.704 --> 23:17.664
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:17.664 --> 23:19.291
- Seven minutes to go--
I'm getting nervous

23:19.291 --> 23:21.084
for the guys to get
them nice and sharp.

23:21.084 --> 23:23.587
<i>- Usually I can sharpen things</i>
<i>quite fast.</i>

23:23.587 --> 23:25.672
I'm usually pretty good
at pulling it off

23:25.672 --> 23:27.758
in the last few seconds.

23:27.758 --> 23:29.509
<i>I'm not sure how well</i>
<i>it'll slice</i>

23:29.509 --> 23:31.345
<i>after smacking</i>
<i>against the tile,</i>

23:31.345 --> 23:32.971
but we'll find out.

23:32.971 --> 23:34.556
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:34.556 --> 23:36.308
<i>- There isn't much time left</i>

23:36.308 --> 23:38.727
to get this thing finished,
but I'm gonna try.

23:38.727 --> 23:41.563
I don't have time to get
that fine edge

23:41.563 --> 23:43.565
that you need
to do the slice test,

23:43.565 --> 23:46.860
<i>but I put quite</i>
<i>the geometry on that</i>

23:46.860 --> 23:48.362
<i>that just favored the chop.</i>

23:48.362 --> 23:50.447
I'm concentrating
on the chop test,

23:50.447 --> 23:54.993
because Matthew's blade is
the one most likely to break.

23:54.993 --> 23:56.953
If Matthew's blade breaks,

23:56.953 --> 23:59.206
I ain't gonna have to worry
about the slice test.

23:59.206 --> 24:01.541
<i>I'm just rolling the dice.</i>

24:01.541 --> 24:02.668
- Ten!

24:02.668 --> 24:03.877
Nine!

24:03.877 --> 24:04.920
Eight!

24:04.920 --> 24:05.962
Seven!

24:05.962 --> 24:07.089
Six!

24:07.089 --> 24:08.173
Five!

24:08.173 --> 24:10.175
Four! Three!

24:10.175 --> 24:12.302
Two! One!

24:12.302 --> 24:15.013
Bladesmiths,
this handle round is over!

24:15.013 --> 24:16.848
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:16.848 --> 24:18.892
- I'm nervous about
my cracks in the blade,

24:18.892 --> 24:21.395
<i>but I think it is</i>
<i>a functioning chopper.</i>

24:21.395 --> 24:23.105
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:23.105 --> 24:24.815
- Gentlemen,
this is the strength test.

24:24.815 --> 24:26.858
To test the strength
and durability of your edge,

24:26.858 --> 24:28.944
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

24:28.944 --> 24:30.570
I am gonna baton your knives

24:30.570 --> 24:32.989
through these slate tiles
twice.

24:32.989 --> 24:35.826
This brutal test is designed
to push the very limits

24:35.826 --> 24:37.285
of your blade construction.

24:37.285 --> 24:39.287
Matthew, you're up first.
Are you ready?

24:39.287 --> 24:41.665
- Oh, yeah.
- All right, let's do it.

24:41.665 --> 24:43.625
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:43.625 --> 24:45.293
<i>- I am nervous.</i>

24:45.293 --> 24:47.045
<i>The cracks are still</i>
<i>in my head,</i>

24:47.045 --> 24:50.549
and I don't want
my knife to fail.

24:50.549 --> 24:57.431
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:02.436 --> 25:06.314
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:06.314 --> 25:08.734
- Well, Matthew,
first things first--

25:08.734 --> 25:12.237
your edge held up very well--
no wiggling, no chipping.

25:12.237 --> 25:16.158
The handle--little bit
on the small side.

25:16.158 --> 25:17.868
Right up here
where the finger well is,

25:17.868 --> 25:19.870
it's square,
and it's a little bit bite-y.

25:19.870 --> 25:23.206
But, still,
it's hold-on-able,

25:23.206 --> 25:24.416
which is a new word
I just made up.

25:24.416 --> 25:26.209
- [chuckles]

25:26.209 --> 25:29.087
- Overall, it held up nicely.
Well done.

25:29.087 --> 25:30.422
- Thank you.
- Wade, you're up next.

25:30.422 --> 25:31.757
You ready?
- Yeah, I suppose.

25:31.757 --> 25:32.924
- [laughs]

25:32.924 --> 25:34.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:34.968 --> 25:37.179
<i>- I'm worried</i>
<i>going into testing.</i>

25:37.179 --> 25:40.557
<i>I just hope my blade</i>
<i>is usable, it's testable.</i>

25:40.557 --> 25:42.434
I just have
no confidence right now.

25:42.434 --> 25:49.357
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:51.234 --> 25:54.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:54.654 --> 25:57.657
- Well, Wade,
your edge held up very well.

25:57.657 --> 25:59.701
It's a bit obtuse for me.

25:59.701 --> 26:04.247
It's more like a axe edge
than a slicing knife.

26:04.247 --> 26:06.166
There is some gapping here

26:06.166 --> 26:08.794
where the shoulders meet
the guard.

26:08.794 --> 26:10.670
But overall, well done.

26:10.670 --> 26:12.339
- Thank you, sir.

26:12.339 --> 26:13.799
- Christoph, you're up.
- All right.

26:13.799 --> 26:15.383
- You ready?
- Break that puppy.

26:15.383 --> 26:16.885
- I don't want to break it.

26:16.885 --> 26:18.136
- Aw, come on.
- All right, fine.

26:18.136 --> 26:19.805
I'll break it.

26:19.805 --> 26:22.641
<i>- I feel a little bit nervous.</i>

26:22.641 --> 26:25.602
Tile--not very good for edges.

26:25.602 --> 26:30.315
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:30.315 --> 26:33.276
[tiles clatter echoingly]

26:33.276 --> 26:35.445
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:35.445 --> 26:38.031
- Well, Christoph...

26:38.031 --> 26:40.951
out here, where it was
resting on the tile,

26:40.951 --> 26:44.037
your edge held up very well,
but when I hit it,

26:44.037 --> 26:45.580
it put a roll.

26:45.580 --> 26:46.915
[metal pings]

26:46.915 --> 26:47.999
You can hear it...
- Yeah.

26:47.999 --> 26:49.751
- On the edge here.

26:49.751 --> 26:51.378
And I do like the shape
of your handle.

26:51.378 --> 26:53.588
It's a very classic design.

26:53.588 --> 26:55.841
Overall, it held up very well.

26:55.841 --> 26:57.843
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:57.843 --> 26:59.803
- All right, gentlemen,
now that we've brutalized

26:59.803 --> 27:01.555
your blades
in our strength test,

27:01.555 --> 27:02.889
it's time for
the sharpness test.

27:02.889 --> 27:04.474
I'll deliver two blows

27:04.474 --> 27:06.142
to this conveyor belt
with your blade.

27:06.142 --> 27:08.979
Now, a sharp blade
should have no problem.

27:08.979 --> 27:10.730
All right, Matthew, you're up.
You ready?

27:10.730 --> 27:12.148
- Let's do it.
- Okay.

27:12.148 --> 27:18.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:25.620 --> 27:27.998
- [whispering]
Freakin' awesome.

27:27.998 --> 27:30.792
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:30.792 --> 27:32.669
- All right, Matthew,
the blade's sharp.

27:32.669 --> 27:35.422
Second cut...
blew right through.

27:35.422 --> 27:36.881
First cut, when I hit,

27:36.881 --> 27:38.216
this blade just rolled
in my hand.

27:38.216 --> 27:40.135
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:40.135 --> 27:42.721
For me, there's not enough
handle to the blade.

27:42.721 --> 27:45.682
But the blade's sharp.
It's definitely a cutter.

27:45.682 --> 27:47.851
It went through the belt.
Good job.

27:47.851 --> 27:48.852
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:48.852 --> 27:50.312
- Thank you.

27:50.312 --> 27:52.105
- All right, Wade,
you ready?

27:52.105 --> 27:54.524
[laughs]
- I suppose. I don't know.

27:54.524 --> 27:55.692
- [laughing]
That was not a threat.

27:55.692 --> 27:56.693
[laughing]

27:56.693 --> 27:58.737
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:58.737 --> 28:00.447
<i>- I'm worried about the handle</i>
<i>busting through,</i>

28:00.447 --> 28:02.490
something loose
coming undone.

28:02.490 --> 28:04.451
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:04.451 --> 28:07.746
<i>The anticipation is grueling.</i>

28:07.746 --> 28:10.040
<i>I have to hold my arm</i>
<i>to keep my hands from shaking.</i>

28:10.040 --> 28:17.005
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:19.382 --> 28:20.759
[quietly] Oh...

28:23.094 --> 28:24.763
- So, Wade, first off--
I really like

28:24.763 --> 28:26.264
the shape of your handle.

28:26.264 --> 28:27.724
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:27.724 --> 28:29.309
It fits my hand really nicely.

28:29.309 --> 28:31.061
Good chopping edge.

28:31.061 --> 28:33.313
I could take a tree down
with this, easy.

28:33.313 --> 28:35.231
But as far as cutting
this conveyor belt...

28:35.231 --> 28:37.150
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:37.150 --> 28:38.401
It's just not cutting.

28:38.401 --> 28:41.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:41.112 --> 28:43.365
All right, Christoph,
let's do it.

28:43.365 --> 28:49.371
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:49.371 --> 28:51.748
- [sighs]

28:51.748 --> 28:55.418
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:55.418 --> 28:57.545
- Well, I really like
the design of your knife.

28:57.545 --> 29:00.799
Your handle feels wonderful.
I like that simple grip.

29:00.799 --> 29:02.425
The style of
your blade is great.

29:02.425 --> 29:05.178
I just wish it had
more of an edge on it.

29:05.178 --> 29:07.222
I can run my finger
along your edge

29:07.222 --> 29:09.933
without fear of cutting myself.

29:09.933 --> 29:11.351
An edge like that's just not

29:11.351 --> 29:13.186
gonna cut this kind
of material.

29:13.186 --> 29:15.605
<i>- I'm sitting in</i>
<i>the same spot as Christoph.</i>

29:15.605 --> 29:18.660
He has some flaws.
I just think mine are more.

29:21.241 --> 29:22.569
- Well, bladesmiths,
the judges

29:22.569 --> 29:24.821
have watched you work,
tested your blades,

29:24.821 --> 29:26.490
and they've made
their final decision.

29:26.490 --> 29:29.493
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:29.493 --> 29:31.995
Christoph, your blade
did not make the cut.

29:31.995 --> 29:33.789
Doug Marcaida will explain.

29:33.789 --> 29:36.583
- Christoph, this challenge
was physically

29:36.583 --> 29:39.378
and mentally draining,
but your happy attitude

29:39.378 --> 29:41.129
and the way you kept
things lighthearted

29:41.129 --> 29:43.548
kept us smiling,
but at the end of the day,

29:43.548 --> 29:45.467
your blade didn't cut
the conveyor belt,

29:45.467 --> 29:47.636
and on the strength test,
it was the only blade

29:47.636 --> 29:49.012
that took damage,
and that's the reason

29:49.012 --> 29:50.889
we have to let you go.

29:50.889 --> 29:52.516
- Christoph,
please surrender your blade.

29:52.516 --> 29:54.393
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:54.393 --> 29:56.186
<i>- I'm all right</i>
<i>with the judges' decision.</i>

29:56.186 --> 29:58.522
What else are you gonna do?

29:58.522 --> 30:00.482
<i>You're either gonna be gloomy</i>
<i>and annoyed all the time,</i>

30:00.482 --> 30:02.609
or else you'll have fun.

30:02.609 --> 30:04.361
<i>When I get home,</i>
<i>I'll probably mess up</i>

30:04.361 --> 30:05.987
<i>the shop a little more.</i>

30:05.987 --> 30:07.656
<i>My wife and daughter</i>
<i>just said,</i>

30:07.656 --> 30:09.282
<i>"Don't embarrass us too much."</i>

30:09.282 --> 30:10.742
Too late!

30:10.742 --> 30:11.743
Sorry.

30:11.743 --> 30:14.538
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:14.538 --> 30:16.665
- Matthew, Wade,
congratulations.

30:16.665 --> 30:18.125
You've made it
to the final round

30:18.125 --> 30:19.459
of this competition,
which means

30:19.459 --> 30:21.169
that you're both
one step closer

30:21.169 --> 30:23.046
to the title of
"Forged in Fire" champion

30:23.046 --> 30:24.840
and a check for ten grand.

30:24.840 --> 30:26.675
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

30:26.675 --> 30:28.885
to re-create an iconic weapon
from history.

30:28.885 --> 30:31.388
That weapon is...

30:31.388 --> 30:33.515
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:33.515 --> 30:34.850
the Spanish navaja.

30:34.850 --> 30:37.310
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:37.310 --> 30:39.646
<i>Rising to popularity</i>
<i>in the 1600s,</i>

30:39.646 --> 30:42.274
<i>the Spanish navaja was</i>
<i>a deadly, folding weapon,</i>

30:42.274 --> 30:44.985
<i>common in duels</i>
<i>and street brawls.</i>

30:44.985 --> 30:47.070
<i>This blade could be folded</i>
<i>into the handle</i>

30:47.070 --> 30:50.240
<i>and locked in place,</i>
<i>making it easy to conceal.</i>

30:50.240 --> 30:52.576
<i>It featured a locking-ratchet</i>
<i>mechanism,</i>

30:52.576 --> 30:54.619
<i>which kept the blade in place.</i>

30:54.619 --> 30:56.621
<i>The ratchet sound</i>
<i>of a navaja opening</i>

30:56.621 --> 30:58.623
<i>was also used</i>
<i>to intimidate foes.</i>

30:58.623 --> 31:00.542
<i>Wielded with the blade up,</i>

31:00.542 --> 31:02.627
<i>a strike from the navaja</i>
<i>was difficult to parry,</i>

31:02.627 --> 31:04.921
<i>and wounds were often fatal.</i>

31:04.921 --> 31:07.924
<i>Navajas were often inscribed</i>
<i>with pithy phrases in Spanish,</i>

31:07.924 --> 31:10.177
<i>boasting about the deadliness</i>
<i>of the blade.</i>

31:10.177 --> 31:12.929
The Spanish navaja is a folder,

31:12.929 --> 31:16.850
so your navaja must fully open
and fully close,

31:16.850 --> 31:18.894
<i>and when closed,</i>

31:18.894 --> 31:20.687
<i>the edge must be</i>
<i>fully protected by the handle.</i>

31:20.687 --> 31:23.148
Additionally,
your navaja should include

31:23.148 --> 31:25.025
a ratchet-and-lock system,

31:25.025 --> 31:27.652
<i>with at least three points</i>
<i>on the ratchet.</i>

31:27.652 --> 31:29.321
You will have five days

31:29.321 --> 31:30.947
at your home forge
to complete this project.

31:30.947 --> 31:32.908
At the end of five days,
you will return

31:32.908 --> 31:35.786
and present your navajas
to our panel of expert judges.

31:35.786 --> 31:37.871
And only after they've
thoroughly tested those blades

31:37.871 --> 31:40.999
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

31:40.999 --> 31:43.502
and give you a check
for $10,000.

31:43.502 --> 31:46.129
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

31:46.129 --> 31:47.422
- Good luck.
- Dude...

31:47.422 --> 31:49.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:49.466 --> 31:51.676
<i>- So now that I'm back</i>
<i>at my home forge,</i>

31:51.676 --> 31:53.386
<i>I'm comfortable, I'm happy.</i>

31:53.386 --> 31:55.597
I have more tools
that I know how to use

31:55.597 --> 31:57.808
<i>and I'm confident with.</i>

31:57.808 --> 31:59.100
[hammer head clatters]

31:59.100 --> 32:01.978
[snickers]
Cut that out.

32:01.978 --> 32:03.647
<i>I'm gonna use a few</i>
<i>different types of metal--</i>

32:03.647 --> 32:05.857
<i>5920 and 1084,</i>

32:05.857 --> 32:07.150
<i>'cause I know</i>
<i>they'll be flashy,</i>

32:07.150 --> 32:09.027
<i>and I know they'll look nice.</i>

32:09.027 --> 32:11.530
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:11.530 --> 32:13.865
<i>I get through</i>
<i>my first two welding heats,</i>

32:13.865 --> 32:15.992
and immediately I see
this mega-blister.

32:15.992 --> 32:18.078
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:18.078 --> 32:19.871
<i>So that leaves me</i>
<i>pretty much with one option,</i>

32:19.871 --> 32:22.958
and that's to cut...it...out!
[laughs]

32:22.958 --> 32:24.751
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:24.751 --> 32:26.795
<i>Plan B is going to be</i>
<i>work more steel</i>

32:26.795 --> 32:28.672
<i>into this billet.</i>

32:28.672 --> 32:32.008
<i>I'm way behind,</i>
<i>and the clock is ticking.</i>

32:32.008 --> 32:35.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:35.220 --> 32:37.389
<i>- It's great to be back home</i>
<i>at my own home forge,</i>

32:37.389 --> 32:38.890
<i>and I am ready to go.</i>

32:38.890 --> 32:40.433
Well, my plan
on making this blade

32:40.433 --> 32:43.770
is a cable on the spine
for strength,

32:43.770 --> 32:47.274
<i>a ladder-pattern Damascus</i>
<i>on the blade edge,</i>

32:47.274 --> 32:49.276
<i>that's gonna allow me</i>
<i>the sharpness</i>

32:49.276 --> 32:51.361
<i>that I'm looking for.</i>

32:51.361 --> 32:53.238
We're gonna get this heated up.

32:53.238 --> 32:54.865
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:54.865 --> 32:56.950
Matthew's competitive.
He's young.

32:56.950 --> 32:59.870
He's gonna do
everything he can to win it,

32:59.870 --> 33:03.248
and I totally expect
that I can get a piece together

33:03.248 --> 33:05.584
that will outperform his.

33:05.584 --> 33:08.295
About 750 strands
of wire there.

33:08.295 --> 33:11.548
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:11.548 --> 33:13.633
<i>- It's day three,</i>
<i>and I'm working on</i>

33:13.633 --> 33:16.303
<i>a lot of stuff today.</i>

33:16.303 --> 33:19.764
<i>Yesterday I was able to do</i>
<i>the final forging on my blade.</i>

33:19.764 --> 33:23.852
<i>Now it's time to figure out</i>
<i>this ratcheting folder.</i>

33:23.852 --> 33:25.979
<i>This is kind of like</i>
<i>a make-or-break moment for me.</i>

33:25.979 --> 33:27.314
Is this spring gonna work?

33:27.314 --> 33:29.566
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:29.566 --> 33:31.610
If I can get
this thing perfect,

33:31.610 --> 33:35.280
then that can make or break
this competition.

33:35.280 --> 33:36.907
<i>I put everything back</i>
<i>on the plate,</i>

33:36.907 --> 33:39.951
I put it in position, and...

33:39.951 --> 33:42.495
[ratchet clicking]

33:42.495 --> 33:44.915
[clicks tongue]
Voilà.

33:44.915 --> 33:46.291
<i>I'm really happy.</i>

33:46.291 --> 33:47.709
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:47.709 --> 33:49.544
<i>- Okay, going into day three,</i>

33:49.544 --> 33:51.212
<i>I have my blade profiled,</i>
<i>of course.</i>

33:51.212 --> 33:52.881
<i>I'm gonna need to</i>
<i>get it hardened,</i>

33:52.881 --> 33:56.718
<i>but this project</i>
<i>is not going as planned.</i>

33:56.718 --> 33:59.596
<i>I lost my power hammer</i>
<i>yesterday,</i>

33:59.596 --> 34:01.806
and because my power hammer's
out of commission,

34:01.806 --> 34:03.975
<i>there's no room</i>
<i>to start over again.</i>

34:03.975 --> 34:06.561
I'm heating up my blade pattern
on the bottom.

34:06.561 --> 34:09.856
When I hit the color I want,
that's when I'll quench.

34:09.856 --> 34:11.691
<i>I have two days</i>
<i>into this blade.</i>

34:11.691 --> 34:14.110
<i>If there's any problem</i>
<i>during the quench,</i>

34:14.110 --> 34:16.112
I'm back to day one.

34:16.112 --> 34:18.198
<i>Because my power hammer's</i>
<i>out of commission,</i>

34:18.198 --> 34:21.076
<i>I don't have time to do that.</i>

34:21.076 --> 34:22.953
<i>If it doesn't work, I'm done.</i>

34:22.953 --> 34:24.999
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:30.636 --> 34:31.212
I think I got it.

34:31.212 --> 34:33.256
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:33.256 --> 34:34.841
<i>- Yesterday I was able</i>
<i>to get a lot done.</i>

34:34.841 --> 34:37.343
I finalized my spring.
[ratchet clicking]

34:37.343 --> 34:39.387
<i>I got my handle scales</i>
<i>rough shaped.</i>

34:39.387 --> 34:41.473
Today is all about
final assembly.

34:41.473 --> 34:43.933
<i>So I've got</i>
<i>this $5 mokume slammer.</i>

34:43.933 --> 34:45.560
<i>I'm gonna try to forge it out</i>

34:45.560 --> 34:47.395
<i>into a little</i>
<i>rattlesnake tail.</i>

34:47.395 --> 34:50.064
<i>I raided my son's piggy bank.</i>

34:50.064 --> 34:51.816
<i>What would be better</i>
<i>than making</i>

34:51.816 --> 34:55.361
<i>a decorative butt cap</i>
<i>out of quarters?</i>

34:55.361 --> 34:57.906
One of my main concerns with
this knife is the sharpness.

34:57.906 --> 34:59.741
<i>I spent as much time</i>
<i>as I could,</i>

34:59.741 --> 35:01.659
<i>but time's running out.</i>

35:01.659 --> 35:03.453
<i>It's just a "go" moment.</i>
<i>Just go.</i>

35:03.453 --> 35:05.413
Go, go, go, go, go, go, go.
[chuckles]

35:05.413 --> 35:07.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:07.540 --> 35:09.793
<i>I've put so much of my passion</i>
<i>into this blade.</i>

35:09.793 --> 35:11.127
<i>I kept my head down.</i>

35:11.127 --> 35:12.879
<i>I focused. I planned.</i>

35:12.879 --> 35:15.882
<i>I really think I've proven</i>
<i>to myself</i>

35:15.882 --> 35:17.801
<i>that I can make anything.</i>

35:17.801 --> 35:19.677
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:19.677 --> 35:23.973
[whistling softly]

35:23.973 --> 35:25.850
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:25.850 --> 35:28.561
<i>- Last day to finish</i>
<i>this navaja.</i>

35:28.561 --> 35:32.023
My heart's pumping
assembling this piece together.

35:32.023 --> 35:34.859
I'm attaching a pull ring
to the spine of this.

35:34.859 --> 35:36.945
That's what releases
the spring.

35:36.945 --> 35:38.822
<i>Mechanics take time.</i>

35:38.822 --> 35:41.074
<i>The fitting takes time</i>
<i>to get just right.</i>

35:41.074 --> 35:42.742
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:42.742 --> 35:44.953
I'm hoping that time
was well spent

35:44.953 --> 35:47.288
<i>on success and final assembly.</i>

35:47.288 --> 35:48.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:48.540 --> 35:50.250
That's the ticket.

35:50.250 --> 35:52.710
This thing went
together pretty good.

35:52.710 --> 35:53.962
And I really like it.

35:53.962 --> 35:55.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:55.505 --> 35:56.673
It fits tight.

35:56.673 --> 35:58.341
<i>Holding this weapon,</i>

35:58.341 --> 36:01.845
<i>you automatically</i>
<i>feel powerful.</i>

36:01.845 --> 36:04.389
That must be something to do
with the magic in the quench.

36:04.389 --> 36:08.434
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:08.434 --> 36:10.311
- Matthew, Wade,
welcome back to The Forge.

36:10.311 --> 36:12.147
You've had five days
at your home forges

36:12.147 --> 36:13.314
to work on your navajas.

36:13.314 --> 36:14.732
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:14.732 --> 36:16.776
Matthew, how did it go?

36:16.776 --> 36:18.820
- It was the most challenging
blade I've ever made.

36:18.820 --> 36:21.447
<i>I made it out of 1084</i>
<i>and 5920.</i>

36:21.447 --> 36:22.574
<i>It's a gomai.</i>

36:22.574 --> 36:24.701
<i>It has five layers.</i>

36:24.701 --> 36:26.369
<i>I put everything I have</i>
<i>into it--my heart, my soul--</i>

36:26.369 --> 36:28.496
and I hope it performs
very well.

36:28.496 --> 36:30.456
- Wade, how'd it go for you?
- Went good.

36:30.456 --> 36:33.042
It was an interesting weapon
to re-create.

36:33.042 --> 36:36.296
<i>I did a five-layer</i>
<i>composite billet as well.</i>

36:36.296 --> 36:38.006
<i>I went at it</i>
<i>like I was competing</i>

36:38.006 --> 36:39.465
<i>against the world champion.</i>

36:39.465 --> 36:41.050
I did as much as I could

36:41.050 --> 36:43.511
and worked up
right to the last minute.

36:43.511 --> 36:45.180
- All right, gentlemen,

36:45.180 --> 36:46.848
each of your weapons
will now be tested,

36:46.848 --> 36:48.391
and up first, the kill test.
Doug?

36:48.391 --> 36:50.894
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:50.894 --> 36:52.854
- The Spanish navaja--

36:52.854 --> 36:55.273
an iconic folding weapon
from history.

36:55.273 --> 36:57.817
It's even said to influence
the American bowie knife.

36:57.817 --> 36:59.569
To see what kind
of lethal damage

36:59.569 --> 37:01.905
your weapon will do,
we'll take your Spanish navaja

37:01.905 --> 37:04.908
and deliver killing blows
on this deer carcass.

37:04.908 --> 37:06.409
Matthew, you're up first.
You ready?

37:06.409 --> 37:07.452
- Oh, yeah.

37:07.452 --> 37:13.208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:13.208 --> 37:16.252
- Okay, Matthew,
nice and solid work right here.

37:16.252 --> 37:18.379
But I'm still recovering
from an injury.

37:18.379 --> 37:20.715
So please welcome
Anthony Palmer.

37:20.715 --> 37:22.634
Anthony is one
of the chief instructors

37:22.634 --> 37:23.927
of Marcaida Kali.

37:23.927 --> 37:26.054
Today he will have
the pleasure

37:26.054 --> 37:27.889
of wielding
your Spanish navaja.

37:27.889 --> 37:29.891
<i>- My biggest concern</i>
<i>going into testing</i>

37:29.891 --> 37:31.559
is the sharpness of my blade.

37:31.559 --> 37:38.441
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:41.027 --> 37:45.740
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:45.740 --> 37:47.742
- Your blade is beautiful.

37:47.742 --> 37:49.744
And it's also solid
in its feel.

37:49.744 --> 37:51.496
It lacerates easily.

37:51.496 --> 37:53.998
You can see it chopped
right through the spine.

37:53.998 --> 37:55.917
Now, one of the pieces here

37:55.917 --> 37:57.752
came flying out
during the test.

37:57.752 --> 38:01.798
But in terms of the sharpness
and the "wieldability"

38:01.798 --> 38:03.258
of your blade...

38:03.258 --> 38:05.051
it will kill.

38:05.051 --> 38:06.219
- Oh, yeah.

38:06.219 --> 38:07.470
- Okay, Wade, it's your turn.

38:07.470 --> 38:09.347
You ready?
- You bet.

38:09.347 --> 38:13.142
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:13.142 --> 38:17.355
[knife clicking]

38:17.355 --> 38:19.899
- Wade, I can hear
the mechanism working in there.

38:19.899 --> 38:26.781
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:35.623 --> 38:37.750
[carcass thuds]

38:37.750 --> 38:40.211
<i>- The thud of that deer</i>
<i>carcass hitting the floor</i>

38:40.211 --> 38:43.381
is absolutely the sound
of $10,000.

38:43.381 --> 38:46.009
I feel like I'm ahead.
That's where I want to be.

38:46.009 --> 38:47.510
I want to win it.

38:47.510 --> 38:49.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:49.762 --> 38:52.473
- All right, Wade,
your blade is sharp.

38:52.473 --> 38:54.183
- Thank you.

38:54.183 --> 38:56.060
- The one issue is,
it's kind of rickety here,

38:56.060 --> 38:57.979
even while
it was being wielded.

38:57.979 --> 39:02.483
But despite being rickety,
it's deadly, and it will kill.

39:02.483 --> 39:05.111
- Thank you.
- Next up is the strength test.

39:05.111 --> 39:07.155
Ben?
- To test the strength

39:07.155 --> 39:08.698
and durability of your edge,

39:08.698 --> 39:09.949
as well as the overall
construction,

39:09.949 --> 39:11.826
I am gonna smash
into this bamboo

39:11.826 --> 39:12.910
with your Spanish navajas.

39:12.910 --> 39:14.162
Matthew, you're up first.

39:14.162 --> 39:15.413
You ready?
- Oh, yeah.

39:15.413 --> 39:16.748
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:16.748 --> 39:17.915
<i>I'm looking at Wade</i>

39:17.915 --> 39:19.709
like he is one up on me.

39:19.709 --> 39:21.210
<i>His blade might wiggle</i>
<i>a little bit,</i>

39:21.210 --> 39:22.962
<i>but it just cut</i>
<i>that deer in half.</i>

39:22.962 --> 39:24.881
I have to outperform him
on this strength test

39:24.881 --> 39:26.549
if I'm gonna win
this competition.

39:26.549 --> 39:28.319
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:31.668 --> 39:38.509
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:43.931 --> 39:46.183
- Well, Matthew, this thing's
one hell of a chopper.

39:46.183 --> 39:47.768
It held together beautifully.

39:47.768 --> 39:49.686
There was slight glinting
that happened

39:49.686 --> 39:52.397
up here near the tip,
but it's pretty darn sharp.

39:52.397 --> 39:54.733
Very well done.
- Thank you.

39:54.733 --> 39:56.026
- Wade, you're up next.

39:56.026 --> 39:57.986
You ready?
- Yeah.

39:57.986 --> 40:00.239
- [laughs]
- I'm ahead, he's ahead.

40:00.239 --> 40:01.949
I'm ahead, he's ahead.

40:01.949 --> 40:03.826
<i>We've been this way</i>
<i>the whole time.</i>

40:03.826 --> 40:05.494
It's a battle.
I want to win it.

40:05.494 --> 40:12.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:19.341 --> 40:21.093
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:21.093 --> 40:23.011
- [bleep].

40:23.011 --> 40:27.766
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:27.766 --> 40:28.851
[whispering]
No, it's broken.

40:28.851 --> 40:34.356
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:34.356 --> 40:35.941
- [bleep].

40:35.941 --> 40:37.568
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:37.568 --> 40:39.486
- Well, Wade,
we have a problem.

40:39.486 --> 40:41.155
On about the third strike,

40:41.155 --> 40:42.906
things started to get
kind of loose,

40:42.906 --> 40:44.908
and that torquing
and the stress

40:44.908 --> 40:47.202
<i>made your scales pop off.</i>

40:47.202 --> 40:48.996
<i>The only thing holding</i>
<i>the cutting end</i>

40:48.996 --> 40:52.040
to the handle end
are these thin brass sheets,

40:52.040 --> 40:54.543
and I don't have confidence
in their strength.

40:54.543 --> 40:56.753
This blade has lost
its structural integrity.

40:56.753 --> 40:58.547
It's no longer safe to test.

40:58.547 --> 41:01.258
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:01.258 --> 41:03.969
- Wade, due to
the catastrophic failure

41:03.969 --> 41:06.138
of the structural integrity
of your weapon,

41:06.138 --> 41:08.599
we cannot continue testing
that blade.

41:08.599 --> 41:11.226
So I have to ask you
to please leave The Forge.

41:11.226 --> 41:13.562
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:13.562 --> 41:15.731
<i>- I thought I could beat down</i>
<i>a door with that thing,</i>

41:15.731 --> 41:17.691
but, you know,
apparently you can't.

41:17.691 --> 41:19.776
<i>I should've put more weight</i>
<i>in the liner,</i>

41:19.776 --> 41:22.321
just to make
the whole handle section

41:22.321 --> 41:24.781
much more strong.

41:24.781 --> 41:26.450
- Matthew, congratulations.

41:26.450 --> 41:28.535
You are
the "Forged in Fire" champion,

41:28.535 --> 41:30.704
and that's a title that comes
with a check for ten grand.

41:30.704 --> 41:33.040
Good job.

41:33.040 --> 41:34.875
- I just won "Forged in Fire,"

41:34.875 --> 41:37.461
and I am so excited.
[laughs]

41:37.461 --> 41:40.214
<i>Being here as a winner</i>
<i>means a lot to me.</i>

41:40.214 --> 41:42.257
I've had so much support
throughout my life

41:42.257 --> 41:43.884
<i>to do what I am</i>
<i>passionate about,</i>

41:43.884 --> 41:46.136
<i>and my passion</i>
<i>has proven to be</i>

41:46.136 --> 41:47.679
<i>what I should be doing.</i>

41:47.679 --> 41:49.306
I'm supposed to be
a metal-worker.

41:49.306 --> 41:51.934
Stay with it. Don't stop.
Keep going.

41:51.934 --> 41:57.481
<i>♪ ♪</i>
